pitmastR: an R-based pipeline to standardize processing of PIT tag data

1 Getting started with pitmastr

This document is a step-by-step guide to store and work with PIT tag data using ‘pitmastr’ package.

Prior to using pitmastr, users should have the following:

  • A common suffix/prefix appended to all folders containing files downloaded from PIT tag reader.
    • The main function of this package relies on a shared pattern string (i.e., suffix/prefix) to automate the search for files output from the readers.
    • Accordingly, parent folders (those assigned a shared prefix) should only contain the files output from the reader, and should not contain subfolders or other xlsx, txt, or log files within them. (see section ## for example folder structure)
  • A map file, m1, that contains connections between reader (often site names) based on serial number. Dates deployed at each site should be included if necessary (for example, if a reader was relocated to a different site).
  • A second map file, m2, that contains biological variables users want to link to individuals (i.e, sex, species, etc). Note, these data should not be time-varying (age, mass).

2 Load ‘pitmastr’ package

Step 1: Download all files from GitHub Repo: https://github.com/mkailing/pitmastR

Step 2: Load (and install if necessary) ‘devtools’ package to be able to access bundled pitmastr package from local drive or git repo

# if devtools is not already installed, use: 
# install.packages("devtools")

# else, load to library
library(devtools)

Step 3: Install and load bundled ‘pitmastR’ from zip file

3 Data management

3.1 File storage

The way detections on the reader are stored can vary depending on the model type and programmed settings. The folder structure we recommend accommodates most file types output by the readers *See below for caveat regarding .accdb.

  • Data downloaded as .log files will store detections by date in a single file.
  • Newer systems allow for the export of several dates worth of detections into a single .txt or xlsx file.

pitmastR was created with this in mind and by storing as recommended, users can simultaneously assemble all detections from the various filetypes.

*Users with detections stored as .accdb files are encouraged to export the table from MS Access as a .xlsx to be compatible with master file assembly through ‘workhorse’.

![In the above example, there exists multiple readers at a single site that need to remain distinct. Each reader is assigned a name that joins the site and entrance.]

3.2 Map file formats

R objects are highly sensitive to date and time formats. To streamline data manipulations, prior to assembling or manipulating data, format your map files to ensure compatibility with subsequent data assembly functions. The data should be in long format for ease of use. Below is an example of map file structure.

3.2.1 first, prepare your map1 file that contains reader information

‘format_map1’ requires 3 arguments:

  • path.csv, the file path where the map1 file that contains the dates, serial numbers, and locations (e.g., site names) of the readers
  • date1, column name of the deployment date of the readers at the site
  • date2, column name of the ending date for the reader at the site

This function will default to the current date for end date if the reader is still active at a site. In instances where reader files only provide the last four digits of the serial number, format_m1 will backfill the first four with ‘9999.’ to ensure downstream compatibility.

# read in first map file (m1) and auto format with format_map1 function
m1 <- format_m1(path.csv = "/Users/mkailing/Dropbox/Kailing_Projects/pitmastr/inst/demo_dat/sn_map_demo.csv",
                  date1 = start,
                  date2 = end)
#check dataframe

3.2.2 second, prepare your map2 file that contains biological data associated with individuals

‘format_m2’ requires 3 arguments:

  • path.csv, the file path including the name of the map2 file that contains the biological data
  • date1, column name of the sampling dates (or start dates) of the readers at the respective site
  • id.colname, column name that contains pit tag IDs
  • keep.cols, combined list of columns that should be retained
# read in second map file (m2) and auto format with format_map2 function
m2 <- format_m2(path.csv = "/Users/mkailing/Dropbox/Kailing_Projects/pitmastr/inst/demo_dat/bio_map_demo.csv",
                           date1 = date,
                           id.colname = id,
                           keep.cols = c(sex, species, age, mass, site))

Double check that id format is consistent with that of reader files. In our example, id contains a prefix “P_” that is inconsistent with files from reader. So, we remove here for all columns containg tag IDs in each map file.

m1 %>% 
  mutate(test.tag = gsub('P_', "", test.tag)) -> m1
m2 %>% 
  mutate(id = gsub('P_', "", id)) -> m2

4 Data assembly

The first family of functions in pitmastR used to wrangle data stored in PIT tag files are assemblRs. The primary data assembly function (‘workhorse’) will search the user specified directory (path) to find all files output by readers, extract the detections from those files and serial numbers of readers, and assemble them in a master dataframe that can be exported or manipulated subsequently. Objects returned from any of the assembly functions will have shared structure, so they can be combined easily using ‘rbind’ in base R.

4.1 Assemble data…

4.1.1 with ‘workhorse’

The ‘workhorse’ function was built to search all folders within the directory for each of the file types that can be exported by the readers. After extracting the detections from each file iteratively. ‘workhorse’ returns a list object of two dataframes. The first contains all the detections with reader information provided in m1. The second returns a data frame containing only detections of test tags. This object will be used to evaluate reader operation and create survival object. ‘workhorse’ requires three arguments:

  • path, the directory containing folders that store files downloaded from readers
  • string, the shared prefix/suffix appended to all parent folders
  • map.file1, the name of an object created using ‘format_map1’

and a fourth argument is optional:

  • remove.dup, specify whether duplicated detections should be dropped from master dataframe once assembled (i.e., if one row is an exact match to another).
    • This argument defaults to “N”, such that all rows will be retained even if exact matches exist.
    • In most instances, duplicated rows are an artifact of accidentally duplicated data; ‘remove.dup=“Y”’ is strongly suggested.

In our example dataset, the highest folders are the primary site names. Within them, the parent folders contain the prefix “LOGGER_”, which is the pattern we call to the function indicating which folders to search for files containing detections from readers. The path up to the parent folder name will be included as a column in the returned object.

pit_mastr <- workhorse(directory = "/Users/mkailing/Dropbox/Kailing_Projects/pitmastr/inst/demo_dat",
                string="LOGGER",
                map.file1 = m1, 
                remove.dup = TRUE)

# check dataframes

4.2 Link individuals’ metrics to PIT detections using ‘integrate_bio’

The ‘integrate_bio’ function allows users to combine biological metadata on individuals to detections.

‘integrate_bio’ requires three arguments:

  • x, the df containing detections (ie the first object in the ‘pit_mastr’ list)
  • y, the map2 file, m2, containing individual metadata (i.e., species, sex, tag location, tag date) Note: only time-independent variables may properly match. Time-varying factors that get included, such as mass, may not be properly reflected with detection dates
  • joiner, the name of the column containing PIT tag IDs that is shared between the master file and map file 2.

and an optional fourth argument: - remove.tt, removes any test tag detections

pit_workr <- integrate_bio(pit_mastr[[1]],
                           m2,
                           joiner = 'id',
                           remove.tt = TRUE)

head(pit_workr); tail(pit_workr)

5 Data manipulation

This family of functions will create objects that users can use in simple statistical models and survival analyses.

‘bundle_by’ function will return a dataframe with data summarized by PIT tag ID (or other grouping variables) and user-specific date time units. It requires XX arguments:

  • x, the df containing detections and desired grouping variables. In our example, we use the object returned from ‘integrate_bio’
  • obs.groups, a list of column names by which the user wants data to be structured and summarized
  • obs.units, the time unit by which to summarize observations
  • date.colname, column name for date to summarize by

First, we can bundle observations by pit tag id, sex, and detection site, counting the number of days individuals were detected within weeks of the year.

ids_wks <- bundle_by(x = pit_workr,
                             obs.groups =  c(id, sex, site.x),
                             obs.unit = "weeks",
                             date.colname = date)
head(ids_wks); tail(ids_wks)

6 Check status of readers

These functions are to evaluate the consistency (or identify gaps) in system operation, that will support the creation of survival objects (such that days when systems are running are considered a ‘sample event’).

‘readr_check’ will return a dataframe that counts the number of times a test tag was fired (metric used to determine whether reader was working) by date for each system. It requires 3 arguments:

  • x, name of the object containing all test tag detections (e.g., second list object returned from the ‘workhorse’ function)
  • sys.colname, site (i.e., reader) column name in x. This allows user to evaluate coverage of each reader
  • date1, name of date column in x
  • min.reads, minimum number of test tag fires needed in a day for a system to be considered ‘operating’. The value defaults to
rdr_chk <- readr_check(pit_mastr[[2]], 
                       sys.colname = reader, 
                       date1 = date, 
                       min.reads = 2)

‘readr_viz’ will output the dataframe object returned from readr_check as ggplot object. It requires 1 argument:

  • df, name of the dataframe that summarizes test tags fired (e.g., the object returned using readr_check)

  • MACY WILL MAKE THIS PLOT MORE APPEALING!!

rdr_viz <- readr_viz(rdr_chk)

7 Format dataframe for use in ‘survival’ package

pit_survival manipulates previously built data objects and integrates them to a single dataframe object. The returned objectis compatible with the ‘Surv’ function from the ‘survival’ package, which generates a survival object that can be used for estimating various survival curves.

‘pit_survival’ requires five arguments:

  • map.file1, name of the dataframe object returned from format_m1
  • pit_workr, name of the dataframe object containing detections and associated biological data
  • readr_check, name of the dataframe object returned from ‘readr_check’ function
  • min.reads, minimum number of daily test tag fires for a reader to be considered operational
  • min.detects, number of times an individuals should be detected on a date to be considered ‘observed’
pit_surv1 <- pit_survival(m1, 
                          pit_workr, 
                          readr_check = rdr_chk, 
                          min.reads = 2, 
                          min.detects = 1)

The returned object contains two estimates for ‘time’ that users can determine to be most useful. - time_since_lastobs is the number of days since the last observation period, this number can be manipulated if users are interested in interval censored survival analyses - time_since_tagdate is the number of days since the first observation (ie the individuals tag date)
